  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nI_{\\mathrm{CL}}\n=\n\\oint_{\\Gamma} A\\cdot \\mathrm{d}x .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\Gamma$ be a closed causal loop passing through or encircling the TZP.  \nLet $A$ be a one-form potential defined along the loop.\n\nThe infinitesimal contribution of the potential along the path is:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nA\\cdot \\mathrm{d}x .\n\\end{equation}\n\nIntegrating this contribution over the full closed loop gives the loop invariant:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nI_{\\mathrm{CL}}\n=\n\\oint_{\\Gamma} A\\cdot \\mathrm{d}x .\n\\end{equation}\n\nIf $\\mathrm{d}A=0$ away from $p$ and support is concentrated at the TZP, then the loop integral depends only on the causal winding around $p$.\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\n$I_{\\mathrm{CL}}$ records the accumulated causal phase around the TZP. It is invariant under deformations of $\\Gamma$ that preserve the winding relation to $p$.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
